"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515709","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-03","<p>We have no plans to further regulate the sale of black spot carbon monoxide detectors.</p><p>Carbon monoxide detectors fall under the General Product Safety Regulations (GPSR) 2005 which states any product placed on the market must be safe. Trading Standards will remove products that do not meet the requirements of the GPSR.</p><p>These types of carbon monoxide detectors are obsolete and no longer generally available.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-05-03T15:13:04.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515709/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515709/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-26","Carbon Monoxide: Alarms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether he has plans to regulate the sale of black spot carbon monoxide detectors.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","35533"
